{
  "texts": [
    "In the case where the marked content is an image, P SN R is calculated as shown in the following equation:P SN R = 10 log 10 255 2 M SE (d B) (1) M SE = 1 M × N M m=1 N n=1 [ f (m, n) -f w (m, n)] 2(2)where M × N is the size of the image, f and f w are the original and marked images, and M SE is the mean square error between f and f w. In the case of a video and if the number of marked frames is K, we calculate the Mean P SN R as follows:M P SN R = 1 K K k=1 P SN R k (3)Despite its simplicity, P SN R or M P SN R cannot sometimes provide subjective evaluation results, so SS I M or M SS I M are introduced to evaluate visual quality of the marked image or video quality.",
    "The M SS I M is defined as follows:M SS I M = 1 k K k=1 SS I M( f k, f kw) (4) SS I M( f k, f wk) = (2μ f k μ f kw + C 1)(2σ f k f kw + C 2) (μ 2 f k + μ 2 f kw + C 1)(σ 2 f k + σ 2 f kw + C 2) (5)where μ f k and μ f kw are the mean values of the original image and the marked one, respectively; σ f k and σ f kw are the variances of the original image and the marked one.",
    "σ f k f kw denotes the covariance of the original image and the marked one; and C 1 and C 2 are two stability constants.",
    "We note that there exist watermarking techniques that are visible, but their use is limited to specific applications.",
    "The second requirement is capacity (also called payload) which presents the quantity of embedded information in host media."
  ]
}